<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd"><en-note><div>Admin Tools</div><div><br /></div><div><b><font style="font-size: 24px;">How to configure sysstat on Debian</font></b></div><div><br /></div><div>“”” The statistics reported by sar deal with I/O transfer rates,  paging activity, process-related activities, interrupts,  network activity, memory and swap space utilization, CPU  utilization, <a href="http://www.leonardoborda.com/blog/tag/kernel/">kernel</a> activities and TTY statistics, among others. Both UP and SMP machines are fully supported.</div><div>SAR = System Active Reoprted</div><div>“”"</div><div>=&gt; sudo apt-get install sysstat</div><div><br /></div><div># Edit “/etc/default/sysstat and set ENABLE = “true"</div><div>=&gt; sudo vim /etc/default/sysstat</div><div><br /></div><div># You can change the collection interval by editing /etc/cron.d/sysstat</div><div>=&gt; sudo vim /etc/cron.d/sysstat</div><div><br /></div><div># Restart the sysstat</div><div>=&gt; sudo service sysstat restart</div><div><br /></div><div># If you want to see all statistics :</div><div>=&gt; sar -A</div></en-note>